places.name: Kajipara Masjid
places.address: Q8RG+HXG Kajipara Masjid, Baidyabati, West Bengal 712222

featured_reviews.review_id:
It's design is very beautiful from outside. Many people come here to pray.
It is a place of great architecture and immense beauty and can be admired from afar.
There are two mosques in kazipara.
This mosque also called old Masjid or Bari Masjid.

Every Friday, large Muslim population of the Kazipara and nearby villages comes to the masjid and performs the prayer in zamat.

This Mosque is in form of a square-shaped with large entrances at each side, giving the impression of gateways to the spiritual world.
There is a pond at this place.
A common feature in mosques is the minarat the tall, slender tower that usually is situated at one of the corners of the mosque structure. The top of the minaret is always the highest point in mosque.

All mosques have rules regarding cleanliness, as it is an essential part of the worshippers' experience. Muslims before prayer are required to cleanse themselves in an ablution process known as wudu. However, even to those who enter the prayer hall of a mosque without the intention of praying, there are still rules that apply. Shoes must not be worn inside the carpeted prayer hall. Some mosques will also extend that rule to include other parts of the facility even if those other locations are not devoted to prayer. Congregants and visitors to mosques are supposed to be clean themselves. It is also undesirable to come to the mosque after eating something that smells, such as garlic.

During Ramadan, Muslims spend a lot of time at the masjid, or mosque, for special prayers and community events.

featured_reviews.review_id: More than a century old Masjid at Champdani. It exhibits some beautifully carved floral images. In order to maintain the direction of the Qibla a fine use of architectural techniques is employed. Friday surmon delivered by the present Imam Maulana Tufail Attari happens to be very brief, lucid, to the point and free from inciting racial, religious and secterian bigotry.
